Knife

Target IP: 10.129.148.157

Scanning


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this port. Viewing the source-code of this webpage does not provide anything useful. This website is also non-interactive as there are no buttons. Performing a directory search against this application using multiple wordlists did not result in anything useful.


Using Wappalyzer, I collected what the host is using. Then I Googled the different technologies used by the target to find any public exploit. One interesting result I obtained is PHP 8.1.0 used by the host.



I found a verified public working exploit for this PHP version used by the target machine. The exploit contains more information about the vulnerability.

Exploitation


I compiled the exploit above and ran it against the target machine. I gained a simple shell using the exploit. Time to upgrade this to a reverse shell connection.


And now I have a reverse shell connection on port 8444. In the picture above, the terminal on top is where I used the public exploit and sent the reverse shell script to gain a connection. The terminal on bottom is where I gained a reverse shell connection on port 8444 as the user james.

Privilege Escalation


Running sudo -l shows the binary /usr/bin/knife can be used for PE.


And now I have a root shell on the target machine.

Flags


The user.txt flag once I gained a foothold on the machine by using the public exploit.


The root.txt flag once I used /usr/bin/knife to gain a root shell.
